I've modified this a bit to be a general recursion method and thought I'd update here. The following will run a function that updates a value, until predicate returns truthy for that value. It is tail-call optimized and so avoids the call stack in browsers that support it (only webkit/v8 atm). I haven't quite figured out passing multiple parameters to the function yet, but I imagine that could be handled seperately with _.wrap or the like around the passed func. 

```js
_.recurse = (func, predicate, initialVal) => {
  let bounce = (f) => {
    while (_.isFunction(f)) {
      f = f.apply(f.context, f.args)
    }
    return f
  }
  let cursor = (v, nv) => {
    if (predicate(v)) {
      return v
    } else {
      return _.partial(cursor, nv, func(nv))
    }
  }
  return bounce(_.partial(cursor, initialVal, func(initialVal)))
}
```

